etymologies: Old English stærlinc, from stær ‘starling’ (of Germanic origin) + -ling

definitions: a gregarious Old World songbird with a straight bill, typically with dark lustrous or iridescent plumage but sometimes brightly colored.

notes.text: Family Sturnidae (the starling family): many genera and numerous species, in particular the speckled Sturnus vulgaris, widely introduced elsewhere. The starling family also includes the mynahs, grackles, and (usually) the oxpeckers

shortDefinitions: gregarious Old World songbird with straight bill

etymologies: late 17th century: perhaps a corruption of dialect staddling ‘staddle’

definitions: a wooden pile erected with others around or just upstream of a bridge or pier to protect it from the current or floating objects.
shortDefinitions: wooden pile erected with others around or just upstream of bridge or pier
